=========================================================
CONTEXT SWITCHING (C++ INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition
----------

Context switching is the process of the CPU saving the state of one thread/process 
and loading the state of another so execution can continue.

---------------------------------------------------------

Why is Context Switching Needed?

- Multiple threads/processes share a limited number of CPU cores.
- The OS switches between them to give each a chance to execute.

---------------------------------------------------------

What is Saved?

✓ Program Counter (PC)
✓ CPU Registers
✓ Stack Pointer
✓ Thread/Process State

---------------------------------------------------------

Example

Thread A is running.

↓

Time slice expires.

↓

OS saves Thread A's state.

↓

OS loads Thread B's state.

↓

Thread B starts running.

---------------------------------------------------------

Advantages

✓ Enables multitasking
✓ Better CPU utilization
✓ Fair CPU scheduling

---------------------------------------------------------

Disadvantages

✗ CPU time is spent saving/loading state.
✗ Too many context switches reduce performance.
✗ Process context switches are more expensive than thread context switches.

---------------------------------------------------------

Interview Points

✓ Context switching is performed by the Operating System scheduler.
✓ Thread context switching is faster because threads share the same address space.
✓ Process context switching is slower due to separate memory spaces.

---------------------------------------------------------

One-line Interview Answer

"Context switching is the OS mechanism of saving the execution state of one thread or 
process and restoring another so multiple tasks can share the CPU."
